caption: My husband and I ordered burritos. The meat was flavorful, well spiced, and delicious. Veggies in side were fresh. We got two sauces (one more spicy) and both were great. The food here is incredibly good. The dishes are seasoned very well and I think quite unique to all the other Mexican restaurants I've been before. The al pastor burrito is so tasty my family ate half of it stealing bites, despite having eaten their own dinner before I got home. The other thing I really enjoy is that with most tacos, burritos, etc. I have to add things to them to make it good... like sauce, limes, etc. This burrito is perfect exactly as the chef makes it. The food tastes like someone took time to make it and has a homemade-ness about it that has made it a favorite of mine worth telling people about. And the HORCHATA!!! Fresh, creamy, beautiful mouthfeel - not the watery, ice laden, powdered mix that you find at other places. Truly a hidden gem that would not be out of place on any local top 10 list or foodie show.

I can't speak to how good the food was, as they canceled my order after 1 hour and 45 minutes of waiting for it to arrive. They said they were "too busy" to fulfill it. It would be one thing if they canceled immediately after I placed the order, knowing they were busy and couldn't get it delivered on time. But notifying me of this after I had already waited close to two hours, and the food was already 30 minutes late, is just really terrible service.  Oh, and by the way, the restaurant didn't close for another two hours after I was notified that my order was canceled, so it's not like it was too late to rectify the issue and deliver the food. We’re definitely planning on going back.

Quick service and nice staff. Chicken nachos were great, just needed a little salt. I have mixed feelings about their tamales. They have two types of tamales. One is filled with Chicken with a red/brown color inside. The other I believe is spinach and I couldn't figure out the meat. This one had a green tint on the inside. I did not care for the green one at all. The Chicken tasted better but was not anything special. I have had better tasting tamales from other parts of the city. Be sure to try both the red and green salsas. The green has a wonderful avocado taste to it, but the chips are a little thick. The red enchilada sauce is a can't miss. Be sure to try the veggie tacos as well. More than enough to fulfill your dinner needs!

I ordered dinner on a Monday night. The male respondent messed up my order horribly because he couldn't understand English. We called calmly to try to get a partial credit to our credit card and the man didn't want to help. He got an attitude fast and complained to my boyfriend that he should have ordered because he spoke Spanish.  This restaurant might be good if you know Spanish. Otherwise, there is a good chance they will get your order wrong. The woman who took my order couldn't even spell Ashland. She spelled it Ashlane (after I correctly spelled it out to her). That is ridiculous when the street is only three blocks away.  Long story short, instead of giving us the partial credit, he demanded all the food back and voided out the account. I worked at a Mexican restaurant for over 3 years, and someone who spoke English FLUENTLY always answered the phone so this issue wouldn't happen. I would try to order from there again, if they handled the situation better but they didn't. Big disappointment!!! :(

The ingredients tasted like quality and fresh. Yummy quesadillas with queso asadero. I usually get mine with chicken (fresh chunks, not that canned stringy stuff you sometimes get in mexican places).  My friend loves the seasoning in the ground beef tacos. The salsas are awesome- the verde is deliciously spicy, the rojo hints roasted tomatoes. I think this place has great value for the quality and portions you're getting. Its maybe 50 steps from the redline Morse stop.
Fantastic food!!! Awesome prices!!! Best Mexican food in Rogers Park

When we went we got a burrito, an al hambre quesadilla, and a sope. I got the burrito and it was very very good, didn't blow me away, but the quality of the meat is what surprised me–it's very high in case you're wondering. Then I tried the Al Hambre Quesadilla, which is just steak and peppers, and oh my goodness, let me tell you, it was absolutely perfect. Kind of on the greasy side, but not on the sickeningly greasy side of things. Then I tried the sope. I have never had, or heard of, a sope before, but let me tell you it is an absolute treat. It's sort of like a fried corn tortilla, that's puffed up a bit, then topped with your choice of meat and vegetables. It was just so stinkin' good. I can't throw enough praises at this place it's a north side gem.
